{"/service/ndnp/dlc/batch_dlc_1kahlo_ver01/data/sn83045462/0028060205A/1937110301/0097.xml":{"full_text":"I*-*\nWas Business\nRecession\nPlanned?\nIf So, Roosevelt Kept\nIt Secret, Says\nObserver.\nBy DAVID LAWRENCE.\nJUST about a year ago .the New\nDeal was given a vote of confi\ndence by 27,000,000 people and\nthe main reason for it was that\nPresident Roosevelt convinced the\nt voters he had brough the Nation to its\neconomic recovery.\nNo hit-or-miss effort, no opportun\nism. no mere turn of luck, but a well\nrfefined the\nPresident insist\ned, was responsi\nble for the eco\nnomic program.\nToday, in the\ncold aftermath of\na year, the truth\nis slowly emerg\ning. The New\nDeal's own ex\nperts, its group of\neconomists, are\nconfes sing that\nthe election prom\nise was ill-fated\nand that recovery\nIs not only not\n_\nDavid Lawrence.\niivi c, ui^u uint a ov-i iwuo ivnooiuu ill\nbusiness is on the way. Here, for in\nstance. is the official announcement to\nthe farmers of the Nation just issued\nby the staff of the Bureau of Agricul\ntural Economics, assisted by repre\nsentatives of the Agricultural Adjust\nt ment Administration, of the Federal\nExtension Service, of the Federal Bu\nreau of Home Economics and of the\nState agricultural colleges.\n\u201cAn analysis of the general situa\ntion indicates that in the fall of 1937\nthe upswing of the business cycie has\nbeen temporarily halted. Although it\nis impossible to determine definitely\nto what extent the present recession\nwill continue into 1938, the chances\nappear against a sufficiently early vig\norous rise in 1938 to bring the average\nof industrial activity and of consumer\nincomes for that year up to that of\n1937\nLower National Income Seen.\nThen the same statement goes on\nto say:\nme national income for 1938 is\nexpected to be below the high level of\nwhich prevailed in 1937, tentatively\nestimated to be about 69 billion dol\nr lars.\u2019\u2019\nJust the other day the President at\nHyde Park was discouraging in\nquirers who wanted to know if busi\nness would be stimulated by tax re\nvision. He spoke of a progressively in\ncreasing national income and led his\nhearers to believe that a 90 billion or\neven 100 billion dollar income was\nwithin the realm of his thinking for\nthe future. Now it comes out that the\nincreases in national income which\nhave been recorded every year since\n1932 have been halted\u2014for how long\nnobody knows.\nDid the President plan that the na\ntional income should stop growing and\nthat there should be business reces\nsions which would send the shivers up\nrim,\" T_L._;__,\nwnoimoo icui nr ui tutr\ncountry and would cause States and\ncities to worry about increases in\nrelief rolls?\n\u201cPlanned It That Way.\u201d\nIf one is to take what the Presi\ndent said in the autumn of 1935 and\ncompare it with the situation existing\ntoday\u2014just two years later\u2014it will\nbe noted that Mr. Roosevelt believed\nhe had solved the problem of recovery\nand that he had done it notwithstand\ning the current belief that \"pump\npriming\u201d was an artificial device and\nof no enduring value. Speaking at\nCharleston, S. C., on October 23, 1935,\nMr. Roosevelt said:\n\"Yes, we are on the way back\u2014not\nt by mere chance. Not by a turn of the\ncycle. We are coming back more\nsoundly than ever before because we\nplanned it that way, and don\u2019t let\nanybody tell you differently.\u201d\nWas it the President\u2019s plan to have\na series of cycles, a series of booms\nand recessions? Or were up-and\ndown curves merely the product of\n\"old deal\u201d ineptitude and to be for-,\nbidden under the New Deal?\nThe agricultural economists of the\nGovernment have access to every bit\nof official data and much unofficial\ndata from which to formulate their\nadvice to the farmers of the country\non how to adjust themselves to the\nyear ahead. The document is most\ncomprehensive and is, of course, pre\npared without thought of political ef\n*vv.i*s uniud.\nMerely Stating Facts.\nNaturally, the group of official econ\nomists are not discussing the why\nand the wherefore of present business\nconditions, but merely stating facts.\nWhat these economists say is not,\ntherefore, as some thick-and-thin sup\nporters of the New Deai say about\neverything adverse, \u201cmerely Liberty\nLeague propaganda.\u201d There comes a\ntime when the blind followers of the\nNew Deal will have to admit that New\nDeal economics has not worked out\nr veil and that \"something else\u201d must\nbe tried, though not necessarily what\nthe right wingers want.\nThere are in the economists\u2019 report\nsome encouraging words for the inter\nnational co-operationist. As domestic\ntrade declines there is some sign of\nimprovement in international trade.\nGays the official analysis:\n\u201cThe volume of total world trade in\n1936 was 5 per cent larger than in\nv 1935, and during the first quarter of\n1937 it was more than 12 per cent\nlarger than in the corresponding pe\nriod of 1936. Barring new and unfore\nseen complications in international re\nlations, some further improvement in\nTk*nrl(i trnriA Hnrir\u00bbcy i qto i*.\n\u201cThe increased demand for indus\ntrial goods arising from the improved\npurchasing power in the countries sup\nplying these products may be expected\nto influence favorably world industrial\nproduction and world trade.\u201d\nBut the sad truth is that \u201ceconomic\nr planning\" by the New Beal evidently\ncannot iron out the curves in the busi\nness charts nor do away with business\ncycles and if Mr. Roosevelt \u201cplanned\nit that way\u201d he kept his plans secret\ntill he passed the election day of 1936\nand now one year later the economists\nof his own administration are telling\na different story.\n(Copyright, 1937.)\nWhat\u2019s Back of It All\nLord Cecil\u2019s Visit Worries Neutrality Advocates, Es\npecially Since He Is to Call at White House.\nBy H. R. BAUKHAGE.\nIS THE President about to take some lessons on how to bring peace to\nI the world through international action?\nI That's the question certain anxious Washingtonians are asking,\nvery discreetly, as they ponder th<s mission of a distinguished week-end\nWhite House guest who arrives on the eve of the opening of Congress.\nHe is the distinguished Robert Cecil, first viscount, son of the third\nMarquess of Salisbury, high in the British government throughout the\nwar. But announcement of his coming has made less impression than the\ndeluge of cables concerning the arrival of the Windsors.\nLord Cecil was co-author, with Woodrow Wilson and General Smuts,\nof the Covenant of the League of Nations, and in this capacity he may be\na far more important visitor than the popular Duke and his American\nDuchess.\nWhy his lordship should appear to be pussyfooting into our\nmidst isn\u2019t quite clear. As a matter of fact, he isn\u2019t. But apparently\nsome of his friends seem to think he\u2019s too warlike a pacifist to be\ngiven the spotlight in these parlous times.\nAccording, to some of the folk who are fighting tor neutrality, the\nobject of Lord Cecil is to sell American pacifists (and perhaps others,\nincluding a President! on the idea that a little intervention at the right\ntime is a good thing for peace.\nThe view seems logical, since Lord Cecil is interested in a European\nmovement called the international peace campaign.\nThic POmnoitrn inoli is! a*\nideas which a number of Americans\nwon\u2019t like, some all will agree to.\nHere are three and you can make\nyour choice:\n1. Recognition of the sanctity\nof treaties.\n2. Limitation of armament by\ninternational agreement.\n3. Strengthening the League\nof Nations with collective security.\nThp last nna i c nna V\u00ab a\nR/<W IN\nr\\ YOUR\ngjflLOMKHlP\nJm,\nneutralists don't like\u2014It looks like another name for intervention to them.\n\nIt is understood that Lord Cecil is going after the National Peace\nConference in this country\u2014the group of representatives of various pacifist\norganizations\u2014and try to line it up with his program. His outfit had a\nconference in Brussels a year ago last August, and some American dele\ngates who attended shied away because they thought that the organization\nwould agree to war if the issue rose between Fascism and democracy.\nAlso, it was felt that Lord Cecil wanted to get international backing\nof such a concrete nature that, when the League of Nations ruled against\nan \u201caggressor nation,\u201d it could rely on force, if necessary, to back up its\nmandate.\nThat is why some of the American peace groups are afraid of the\nvenerable Briton w'ho is about to week-end on Pennsylvania avenue.\nThey are afraid that, in some of those intimate chats on the\nsofa in the White House, Lord Cecil ivill win President Roosevelt\nover to the interventionist side of the scale and inspire him to back\nup the famous Chicago speech with some kind of action.\na\nThe day after election day last year, the Rev. Gerald L. K. Smith was,\n'\u2019\"''\u201c\"\u201cft vv/ uwu .'Uniciurm, ill uuihuic viie. nc uay Deiorc election\nthis year, he waa consorting with the great (outside the New Deal) and\nhad enough money to make a down payment, according to his own state\nment, on a $96,000 radio hook-up.\nSelf-appointed head of the \u201ccommittee of a million.\u201d the ardent\nevangelist-crusader is getting ready to go after the President, the New\nDeal. John Lewis et al. hammer and tongs with the zeal he learned when\nhe was a lieutenant of the late Huey Long.\nMr. Smith may or may not build up a following as important\u2014or\nunimportant\u2014politically as Father Coughlin's (whose network he is taking\nover), but he has a long-time program ahead.\nHe believes the Anti-Saloon League was the greatest pressure group\never organized in American politics, but he says it made one mistake.\nThey had a bad name. They put in \u2018\u2018anti-saloon\u201d and then put the saloon\nout of business. And that put them out.\nMr. Smith makes no such mistake. He is anti-nothing on paper.\nHe is just a \u201ccommittee of a million\u2019\u2019 fighting against \u201cconcentrating\nauthority in the hands of the President,\u201d a \u201ctendency to establish\nan industrial dictatorship\u201d\u2014he is by no means limiting the worlds\nhe has to conquer.\nHow much impression his announced plans have made, if any, on the\nNew Deal scene so far, it is hard to say. He might become an important\nfactor.\nsir Or\n'ANOTHER STAR\nIS BORN\"\n0\nSecretary Wallace must be\ngetting jealous of the President.\nAnyhow, he has picked one of his\nace aides, M. S. Eisenhower, as\n\u2018co-ordinator.\u201d Mr. Eisenhower,\nunlike Secretary James, will limit\nhis co-ordinating to within the De\nipartment of Agriculture.\nWith so many agencies at\n\\i work trying to improve the lot of\nthe farmer, they sometimes stepped\non eacn otners toes, It seems. This\nis understandable. It would be a little embarrassing, just after an adviser\nfrom one division had advised a farmer to plant grass, to have another\nexpert from another division decide that maybe wheat would be just the\nthing. Some one, too, has to say whether a farm should be handled as a\nproblem for the farm tenant people or used for soil conservation purposes.\nMr. Eisenhower, who is an old hand at departmental matters, having\nserved since the days of Secretary Jardine in 1928, will make surveys,\nreview and co-ordinate the work. The new co-ordinator has held more jobs\nthan his rival at the other end of the Avenue. /He has served two years in\nthe foreign service and has taught agricultural journalism. He will handle\nthe work of a dozen divisions.\n(Copyright, 1937, by the North American Newspaper Alliance. Inc.)\n'UrSSmiMmmMM\nThen A Doctor Told Him\u2014\"Just rub in Omega Oil!\"\nWHEN your muscles ache and\nthrob\u2014when pain and stiff\nness is misery \u2014just rub in this\npenetrating liniment and get relief\nquick! Starts easing that pain the\nminute you rub it in. Penetration\ndoes it! Brings warming comfort\ninto your muscles with speed.\nNo one knows more about lini\nments than athletic train\ners. In every field of sport\nthese experts rely on Omega Oil.\nThey know it\u2019s extra-strong, yet\nertra-safe. No bum or blister\nideal for women and children!\nWhy don\u2019t you try this liniment\nwhich is endorsed by so many doc\ntors, nurses and other authorities?\nGet a 35* bottle\u2014and rub muscu\nlar pain and congestion out.\nI\nOCTOBER 30th to NOVEMBER 6th\nINCLUSIVE\nxour Only Opportunity to See\nand Compare the New 1938\nAutomobiles Side by Side!\nadmission:\nDaily, 11 A.M. to 6 P.M.__25c\nEvenings, 6 P.M. to 11 P.M._ 40c\nSee Those Radio Broadcasts From the Show! Thurt., Nov. 4th.\nWMAL: \"Borneo A Orch\u201d WOL: \u201cTony Wahemon\u201d\n3:00 to 3:IS P.M. 0:00 to 0:15 P.M.\nWJSV: \"Arch McDonald\" WJSV: \"Arch McDonald\"\nS:30 to 8:48 P.M. 8:18 to 8:30 P.M,\nWRC: \"Cordon Hittonmark\u201d\n7:48 to 8:00 P.M.\nAUTOMOTIVE EXHIBIT HALL\n24th ST. N.W. BETWEEN M N\nh t\nTHE opinions oj the writers on this page are their own, not\nneccaaarfZj/ The Star\u2019s. Such opinions are presented in\nThe Star\u2019s effort to give all sides of questions of interest to its\nreaders, although such opinions may be contradictory among\nthemselves and. directly opposed to The Star\u2019s.\nA Nuisance Answer\nEarnest Question on Capital Gains Tax Draws\nPresidential Slap.\nBy DOROTHY THOMPSON.\ni1 N HONEST- question, it seemi\nto me, deserves an honest\nanswe^. At his press con\nA ference on Friday, Presi\ndent Roosevelt was asked concerning\nthe prospects of revision of the surplui\nprofits and capital gains taxes. Ar\nhonest answer would have been that\nalthough the administration was not\nready to announce a decision one way\nor the other with respect to tax\naujuawnems, u,\nwas very earnestly r<\nconsidering both\nthe financial pol-\nIcy and the tax\nstructure with a\nview to doing\neverything it\ncould to meet an\nunforeseen crisis.\nInstead, the Pres\nident again re\nferred to the \"ill\nfed, ill clothed, ill\nhoused one-third\nof the American\npopulation\u201d as\nbeing his chief\nonH im.\nDorothy Thompson.\nplied by open insinuation that the\npublic concern over New Deal financial\nand taxation policy emanates solelj\nfrom selfish interests.\nMr. Roosevelt knows that this is\npot true. Mr. Roosevelt knows that\na reconsideration of policy is being\ndemanded not in order to favor the\nwealthy but in order to recreate\nor to save the jobs of millions of\npeople.\nThis column, which was the first,\nbelieve, to call attention candidly tc\nthe realities of a brutal situation did\nit in no carping spirit, but as an appeal\nto realism and co-operation.\nThis is no time\u2014if there ever wa;\none\u2014to emphasize a contrast or con\nflict of interests between classes\nFor the tenth consecutive time th\u00ab\nbusiness index of the last week show)\na sharp decline.\nIn. Gary, Ind., steel workers are\nemployed for only three days a week;\nin many Pittsburgh plants for only\n2 days. Some steel plants have shut\ndown. Freight car loadings for th(\nweek of October 23 were less than lot\nthe corresponding week of 1936 by\n5.4 per cent.\nIt is obviously only a question oi\ntime before the effect of this trend ir\nbusiness must be felt in the purchasing\npower of the people.\nUnless this development is arrested\nquickly and effectively, we may say\ngood by to the social objectives of the\nNew Deal.\nUp to a fortnight ago it may have\nbeen doubtful whether the President\nrealized the seriousness of the situa\ntion. It cannot be doubted any more\nThe whole country knows now that\nthis business recession has not devel\noped in the normal course of a\ntrade cycle. Th country knows that\nIt is seeing an inparalleled example\nof a Government-made depression,\nbrought about by short-sightedness,\nbad Judgment, ineptitude, and a policy\nwhich, starting out to balance pros\nperity, ended by unbalancing recovery.\nHow the Government made this\ndepression has been sketched in this\ncolumn before. Beginning in spring.\n1937, the Treasury initiated a serious\nattempt to balance the budget.\nThe Treasury contracted spending\nto a degree which the public did not\nnotice, so that, beginning with the\nthird quarter of this year, it not only\nadded nothing more to the purchasing\npower of the people, but was with\ndrawing several hundred millions in\nexcess of expenditure.\nHaving added about four billion dol\nlars to the purchasing power of the\nNation in 1936, beginning with June\nof this year it began reducing the\nnational debt at the pace of about\na billion a year.\nSo far, so good. But apparently\nwithout the slightest attention to what\nthe Treasury was doing, the Federal\nReserve Board, embarking on a defla\ntionary policy of its own, raised the\nreserve requirements of the banks up\nto the limit of the law and sterilized\nabout a billion and a half of gold.\nAll this is typical of the behavior\nof the New Deal. There is no quarrel\nabout intentions. It might have been\ndesirable to do something about an\nincipient boom in the spring of 1937,\nlinrfpr t.h* formula of ironintr out. th*\npeaks and valleys of the trade cycle.\nBut, as so often, what was done was\ndone without adequate thought, with\nout consideration of consequences, by\ninept means and in a pernicious\nhurry.\nThe effect of this policy would, of\ncourse, have been less radical if the\nbody to which the cure was admin\nistered had not been weakened by\nfour years of rough treatment. It is\nnow apparent to all but the willful\nthat the policies of the New Deal\nhave been depriving the economic\nbody of its powers of resistance.\nInside the capitalistic, or a semi\ncapitalistic, system, the demand for a\nreversal of the tax policy Is not made\nin the interest of certain selfish,\nwealthy groups, but in the interests\nof a functioning economy. The un\ndistributed profits tax is much liked\nby stockholders. They get\u2014for the\ntime being\u2014higher dividends. But It\nworks to prevent the small and middle\nsized industries from capitalizing\nthemselves.\nThis column has no doubt that the\nGovernment is at this moment weigh\ning carefully sensible and necessary\nmeasures to be taken. Why, then,\nwhile he wait for a reasonable and\nreassuring word, must we get one\nwhich insults the intelligence?\n(Copyrlsht. 1P3T.)\nThis Changing World\nAdministration\u2019s Chief Worry Now Is How Far Be\nhind Britain Will Lag at Brussels.\nBy CONSTANTINE BROWN.\nANTHONY EDEN informed the world on Monday that Great Britain\nwould not rush in front nor lag behind the United State* in the\nFar Eastern question.\nNobody here expected Great Britain to rush in front of us.\nThe one thing that worries the administration is how far they will lag\nbehind.\nThere have been certain oc\ncasions, like in 1931 and 1932, when\nthe British government stayed so\nfar behind that poor Secretary\n2 Henry L. Stimson could not even\nI see It.\n1 Nobody can quite make out\nA whether we had rushed too fast\nin ahead or whether the British had\n1/ stayed too far behind.\nOne ot the. manii nlenn\nant jobs Ambassador Nor\nman Davis will have at Brussels will be to approximate the speed the\nBritish may use in following us. They might start a few paces be\nhind us\u2014that would be immaterial. But the danger is that once we\nhave started the British might lose breath and not be able to\nfollow us at all.\nA distinguished British lecturer a few days ago wisely remarked that\nthe individual who pulls the chestnuts out of the fire generally keeps\nthe chestnut. That may be true, except that it frequently happens that\nhis fingers are so badly burned that he can no longer hold on to it and\nsome bystander picks it up and gets away with it.\n\nWhen Congress meets again on November 15 there will be a good deal\nof talk regarding who caused the summoning of the Brussels conference.\nThe impression the British Foreign Secretary conveyed last night was\nthat Washington was behind the League of Nations and Belgium to call\nthe conference.\nWhether this is technically correct or not is immaterial. The United\nState* Government was and remains vitally interested in the nine-power\npact and did use its influence to bring about a conference to discuss\nJapan's high-handed method* in China.\nAn American\nYou Should\nKnow\nMichael McDermott\u2019s\nOffice One of\nBusiest.\nnBy DELIA PYNCHON.\nICHAEL JAMES MCDER\nMOTT, affectionately dubbed\n\u201cMack\u201d by hi* host of friend*,\nhead* the Department of\nState'* Division of Current Informa\ntion. McDermott has served under the\nregimes of Secretaries Bainbridge\nColby, Prank B-- Kellogg. Charles\nEvans Hughes, Cordell Hull.\nHe knows what the press wants,\nknows where to get it, what can be\nused and what canpot from long ex\nperience. An Irishman from Peabody,\nMass., he handles hi* delicate Job\nwith true Irish ze*t and tact. Hie\nwhite hair fairly bristles with energy.\nHis smile is engaging. His eyes, blue\nand merry, miss little.\nIn the present state of international\ncrisis, he is perhaps the most impor\ntant press officer in Washington out\nside of the White House. His office\nbulges with eager news reporters.\nHe certainly does not try to domi\nnate the press, give out biased propa\nunwun, uic VU\u00ab\u201d\ntained in a recent Chicago newspaper\nto the effect that their Washington\ncorrespondents are alone \u2018'undomi\nnated. McDermott has an enviable\nreputation of saying no more than he\nshould opportunely. He interprets Sec\nretary Hull's official viewpoint fairly,\nplays ball with the press, who in turn\nnever violate his confidence. Sur\nrounded by history in the making, he\nhas the simple informal manner that\nreal people always have. He has had\nover the years an affinity for being\npresent during historic crises.\nWashington saw him first in 1917\npointing for naval war service. Fate\ndetoured him. He was deleaated to\nthe White House to work with Joseph\nTumulty on the secretariat for several\nmonths. He took an examination in\nthe War Department, went overseas,\nwith all his war tools, destination un\nknown, landed in the American\nsection of the Supreme War Council.\nAs secretary to Gen. Bliss he was on\nhand when the treaty of Versailles was\nsigned in Paris, became secretary to\nElihu Root at The Hague, came to the\nState Department in 1920.\nMcDermott\u2019s side expeditions have\nbeen dramatic. The biggest press story\nhe ever had to handle was in 1923.\nThe White House borrowed him to\nwork with Judson C. Welliver on Presi\ndent Harding's ill-fated Alaskan trip.\nHe spent three days without sleep at a\nSan Francisco Hotel, where President\nHarding died, flashing the tragic news\nto the world. There was plenty of ex\ncitement at the famous Pan-American\nConference that McDermott attended\nin 1928; much to remember witness\ning the signing of the Kellogg-Briand\npeace pact.\nAs to hobbies\u2014Mr. McDermott says\nhe has none. He is waiting for his son\n\u2019\u2019Mickey,\u201d aged 4. to grow up so that\nthey can enjoy some together.\nWashington was sorry to see the other treaties thrown in the\nash can. But after all we had no paramount interests in what\nHitler and Mussolini did to the treaty of yarsailles or to the\nLocarno agreement.\nWhen the Japanese followed suit and treated with the same contempt\nthe nine-power pact, the administration did everything possible to get the\nother signatories to assemble somewhere and discuss the situation.\n\nThose who accuse the League of Nations of being indifferent to\nChina's welfare are wrong. The League remains, like in the past, keenly\ninterested in the well-being of the Chinese.\nOnly recently the subcommittee of\u00bbthe Committee on International\nPublic Health studied the sanitary conditions of China and the Chinese\npeople.\nThe subcommittee deplored the fact that a majority of the Chinese\ndo not brush their teeth twice a day. In some cases, it was reported by\noutstanding authorities who studied\nthis question in all its details, they\ndo not brush their teeth for years.\nThe League of Nations will take\nthe necessary steps to put an end\nto such a deplorable state of affairs.\nA special commission will soon be\nappointed to go thoroughly into\nthis matter, which has also an im\nportant economic aspect. If the\nChinese can be induced to take\nbetter care of their teeth there will\nbe at least a boomlet in the tooth\nLeague is not dead yet, after all.\nsrush and tooth paste industry. The\nThe Soviet government has acquired lately a considerable interest in\nthe Skoda arms factories in Czechoslovakia. The Skoda works are about\nas large and profitable as the Krupp Essen works, Vickers Armstrong in\nEngland and Creuzot in France.\nBut it appears that the Russians are less interested in the profits the\nmerchants of death axe making than in controlling Skoda's production.\nThe Chinese are now purchasing there a good deal of war material,\nwhich is being sent via Siberia.\nThis is a long, difficult method of obtaining war material. But while\nit has undoubted disadvantages it has advantages, too. It makes it almost\nimpossible for the Japanese to prevent that war material from reaching\nChina. Neither the Japanese Army nor the air force are in a position to\nprevent these shipments.\nTonight\u2014soothe and relax those tired\nnerves that are probably keeping you\nawake, with nature's own \"nightcap\"\n\u2014a glass of milk warmed just enough\nto take off the chill.\nSleepless nights take a terrific toll from\nthe nervous system a toll which is\nsoon reflected in your eyes, your skin\nin your whole appearance.\nTry a milk nightcap for a month and\nyou\u2019ll be surprised how it soothes and\nf .1 _ .1\nffom the most highly approved nearby\nfarms the milk that is approved for\ni\nicittArs muse icusc ucrvcs uiai\nare probably keeping you\nawake; you\u2019ll be surprised how\nmuch better you look and feel.\nStart tonight on this sensible\nbedtime habit. Order Chestnut\nFarms-Chevy Chase Sealtest\nMilk\u2014the milk that comes only\nijuaiuy, purity anu aaiety oy me\ngreat Sealtest System of Labora\ntory Protection.\nTelephone DEcatur 1011,\norder from your Chestnut\nFarms-Chevy Chase milk\nman, or buy at your favorite\nstore.\ni Enjoy the Stillest Ruing Mmsteil Stir Program, Sundays, 10 P. M., WRC\nCHESTNUT FARMS -CHEVY CHASE MILK\n26\u00bbh STREET AT PENNSYLVANIA AVENUE\nIN WASHINGTON, CHESTNUT FA RMS-CHEVY 'CHASE S E A LT E S T MILK IS SEALTEST APPROVED\n1","height":"31216","width":"22356"}}
